result.execSummary:
The defendant Jed J Flannery was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Theft-Movable Property <=$2500, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.20(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Jed J Flannery in court with attorney Paul Steven Screnock.  Richard J Dufour appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
  Atty Dufour states plea agreement.  Upon the defendant's plea and prior to adjudication, defendant will enter into a Deferred Prosecution Agreement for a period of: 5 years.  Amend at end.  Atty Screnock agrees.  Defendant enters No Contest plea.  Court questions defendant regarding plea. Advises of Constitutional Rights and elements of the charge.  Court finds plea made knowingly, voluntarily & intelligently.  Atty Dufour relies on the testimony at the preliminary hearing for a factual basis.  Atty Screnock stipulates.  BY THE COURT:  Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.  Court accepts defendant's plea and accepts the DPA.  Bond on file:  $150 to be applied to DPA fee and the balance is to be returned.  Defendant to keep address current with the Clerk of Courts and District Attorney.
